# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: annelid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala were long thought to be a discrete phylum.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Recent genome analysis has shown that they are descended from, and should be considered as, highly modified rotifers.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] This unified taxon is sometimes known as Syndermata, or simply as Rotifera, with the acanthocephalans described as a subclass of a rotifer class Hemirotatoria.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The earliest recognisable description of Acanthocephala – a worm with a proboscis armed with hooks – was made by Italian author Francesco Redi (1684).
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] In 1771, Joseph Koelreuter proposed the name Acanthocephala.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Philipp Ludwig Statius Müller independently called them *Echinorhynchus* in 1776.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Karl Rudolphi in 1809 formally named them Acanthocephala.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The oldest known member of the group is the Middle Jurassic (living approximately 165 million years ago) taxon *Juracanthocephalus daohugouensis* known from the Jiulongshan Formation (China).
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The fossil record of the group also includes eggs found in a coprolite from the Late Cretaceous Bauru Group of Brazil, around 70–80 million years old, likely from a crocodyliform.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The group may have originated substantially earlier.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans are highly adapted to a parasitic mode of life, and have lost many organs and structures through evolutionary processes.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] This makes determining relationships with other higher taxa through morphological comparison problematic.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] A 2016 phylogenetic analysis of the gene order in the mitochondria suggests that Seisonidea and Acanthocephala are sister clades and that the Eurotatoria are the sister clade to this group, producing the cladogram below.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Several morphological characteristics distinguish acanthocephalans from other phyla of parasitic worms.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans lack a mouth or alimentary canal.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] This is a feature they share with the cestoda (tapeworms), although the two groups are not closely related.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Adult stages live in the intestines of their host and uptake nutrients which have been digested by the host, directly, through their body surface.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The acanthocephalans lack an excretory system, although some species have been shown to possess flame cells (protonephridia).
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The most notable feature of the acanthocephala is the presence of an anterior, protrudable proboscis that is usually covered with spiny hooks (hence the common name: thorny or spiny headed worm).
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The proboscis bears rings of recurved hooks arranged in horizontal rows, and it is by means of these hooks that the animal attaches itself to the tissues of its host.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The hooks may be of two or three shapes, usually: longer, more slender hooks are arranged along the length of the proboscis, with several rows of more sturdy, shorter nasal hooks around the base of the proboscis.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The proboscis is used to pierce the gut wall of the final host, and hold the parasite fast while it completes its life cycle.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Like the body, the proboscis is hollow, and its cavity is separated from the body cavity by a *septum* or *proboscis sheath*.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Traversing the cavity of the proboscis are muscle-strands inserted into the tip of the proboscis at one end and into the septum at the other.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Their contraction causes the proboscis to be invaginated into its cavity.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The whole proboscis apparatus can also be, at least partially, withdrawn into the body cavity, and this is effected by two retractor muscles which run from the posterior aspect of the septum to the body wall.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Some of the acanthocephalans (perforating acanthocephalans) can insert their proboscis in the intestine of the host and open the way to the abdominal cavity.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The size of these animals varies greatly, ranging from a few millimetres in length to *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus*, which measures from 10 to 65 centimetres (3.9 to 25.6 in).
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] A curious feature shared by both larva and adult is the large size of many of the cells, e.g. the nerve cells and cells forming the uterine bell.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Polyploidy is common, with up to 343n having been recorded in some species.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The body surface of the acanthocephala is peculiar.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Externally, the skin has a thin tegument that covers the epidermis and consists of a syncytium with no cell walls.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The syncytium is traversed by a series of branching tubules containing fluid and is controlled by a few wandering, amoeboid nuclei.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Inside the syncytium is an irregular layer of circular muscle fibres, and within this again some rather scattered longitudinal fibres; there is no endothelium.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] In their micro-structure the muscular fibres resemble those of nematodes.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Except for the absence of the longitudinal fibres the skin of the proboscis resembles that of the body, but the fluid-containing tubules of the proboscis are shut off from those of the body.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The canals of the proboscis open into a circular vessel which runs round its base.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] From the circular canal two sac-like projections called the *lemnisci* run into the cavity of the body, alongside the proboscis cavity.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Each consists of a prolongation of the syncytial material of the proboscis skin, penetrated by canals and sheathed with a muscular coat.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] They seem to act as reservoirs into which the fluid which is used to keep the proboscis "erect" can withdraw when it is retracted, and from which the fluid can be driven out when it is wished to expand the proboscis.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The central ganglion of the nervous system lies behind the proboscis sheath or septum.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] It innervates the proboscis and projects two stout trunks posteriorly which supply the body.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Each of these trunks is surrounded by muscles, and this nerve-muscle complex is called a *retinaculum*.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] In the male at least there is also a genital ganglion.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Some scattered papillae may possibly be sense-organs.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans have complex life cycles, involving a number of hosts, for both developmental and resting stages.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Complete life cycles have been worked out for only 25 species.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala are dioecious (an individual organism is either male or female).
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] There is a structure called the *genital ligament* which runs from the posterior end of the proboscis sheath to the posterior end of the body.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] In the male, two testes lie on either side of this.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Each opens in a vas deferens which bears three diverticula or *vesiculae seminales*.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The male also possesses three pairs of cement glands, found behind the testes, which pour their secretions through a duct into the vasa deferentia.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] These unite and end in a penis which opens posteriorly.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] In the female, the ovaries are found, like the testes, as rounded bodies along the ligament.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] From the ovaries, masses of ova dehisce into the body cavity, floating in its fluids for fertilization by male's sperm.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] After fertilization, each egg contains a developing embryo.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] (These embryos hatch into first stage larva.) The fertilized eggs are brought into the uterus by actions of the *uterine bell*, a funnel like opening continuous with the uterus.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] At the junction of the bell and the uterus there is a second, smaller opening situated dorsally.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The bell "swallows" the matured eggs and passes them on into the uterus.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] (Immature embryos are passed back into the body cavity through the dorsal opening.) From the uterus, mature eggs leave the female's body via her oviduct, pass into the host's alimentary canal and are expelled from the host's body within feces.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Having been expelled by the female, the acanthocephalan egg is released along with the feces of the host.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] For development to occur, the egg, containing the acanthor, needs to be ingested by an arthropod, usually a crustacean (there is one known life cycle which uses a mollusc as a first intermediate host).
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Inside the intermediate host, the acanthor is released from the egg and develops into an acanthella.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] It then penetrates the gut wall, moves into the body cavity, encysts, and begins transformation into the infective cystacanth stage.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] This form has all the organs of the adult save the reproductive ones.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The parasite is released when the first intermediate host is ingested.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] This can be by a suitable final host, in which case the cystacanth develops into a mature adult, or by a paratenic host, in which the parasite again forms a cyst.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] When consumed by a suitable final host, the cycstacant *excysts*, everts its proboscis and pierces the gut wall.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] It then feeds, grows and develops its sexual organs.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The male uses the excretions of its *cement glands* to plug the vagina of the female, preventing subsequent matings from occurring.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Embryos develop inside the female, and the life cycle repeats.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Thorny-headed worms begin their life cycle inside invertebrates that reside in marine or freshwater systems.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] One example is *Polymorphus paradoxus.* *Gammarus lacustris*, a small crustacean that inhabits ponds and rivers, is one invertebrate that *P. paradoxus* may occupy; ducks are one of the definitive hosts.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] This crustacean is preyed on by ducks and hides by avoiding light and staying away from the surface.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] However, infection by *P. paradoxus* changes its behavior and appearance in a number of ways that increase its chance of being eaten.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] First, infection significantly reduces *G. lacustris'*s photophobia; as a result, it becomes attracted toward light and swims to the surface.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Second, an infected organism will even go so far as to find a rock or a plant on the surface, clamp its mouth down, and latch on, making it easy prey for the duck.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Finally, infection reduces the pigment distribution and amount in *G. lacustris,* causing the host to turn blue; unlike their normal brown colour, this makes the crustacean stand out and increases the chance the duck will see it.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Experiments have shown that altered serotonin levels are likely responsible for at least some of these changes in behaviour.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] One experiment found that serotonin induces clinging behavior in *G. lacustris* similar to that seen in infected organisms.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Another showed that infected *G. lacustris* had approximately 3 times as many serotonin-producing sites in its ventral nerve cord.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalosis, a disease caused by *Acanthacephalus* infection, is prevalent in aquaculture, occurring in Atlantic salmon, rainbow and brown trout, tilapia, and tambaqui.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Increasing occurrence in Brazilian farming of tambaqui has been reported, and in 2003 *Acanthacephalus* was first reported in cultured red snapper in Taiwan.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The life cycle of *Polymorphus* spp. normally occurs between sea ducks (e.g. eiders and scoters) and small crabs.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Infections found in commercial-sized lobsters in Canada were probably acquired from crabs that form an important dietary item of lobsters.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Cystacanths occurring in lobsters can cause economic loss to fishermen.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] There are no known methods of prevention or control.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Although they rarely infect humans, worms in the phylum Acanthocephala cause the disease acanthocephaliasis in humans.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The earliest known infection was found in a prehistoric man in Utah.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] This infection was dated to 1869 ± 160 BC.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The species involved was thought to be *Moniliformis clarki* which is still common in the area.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The first report of an isolate in historic times was by Lambl in 1859 when he isolated *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus* from a child in Prague.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Lindemann in 1865 reported that this organism was commonly isolated in Russia.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The reason for this was discovered by Schneider in 1871 when he found that an intermediate host, the scarabaeid beetle grub, was commonly eaten raw.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] The first report of clinical symptoms was by Calandruccio who in 1888 while in Italy infected himself by ingesting larvae.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] He reported gastrointestinal disturbances and shed eggs in two weeks.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Subsequent natural infections have since been reported.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Eight species have been isolated from humans to date.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] *Moniliformis moniliformis* is the most common isolate.
[src:annelid/acanthocephala] Other isolates include *Acanthocephalus bufonis* and *Corynosoma strumosum*.
[src:annelid/aciculata] The phylogeny of polychaetes is slowly being resolved.
[src:annelid/aciculata] Errantia and Sedentaria are the two biggest clades of polychaetes, and together they compose clade Pleistoannelida.
[src:annelid/aciculata] Two groups are nested within Errantia: Aciculata (Eunicida + Phyllodocida) and Protodriliformia (small meiofaunal worms such as the Protodrilida).
[src:annelid/aciculata] Historically, the order Amphinomida was part of this subclass.
[src:annelid/aciculata] However, phylogenetic analyses place Amphinomida inside a basal clade with Sipunculida and *Lobatocerebrum*, and this clade is the sister group to Pleistoannelida.
[src:annelid/aciculata] Some taxa, such as Spintheridae and Myzostomida, are still difficult to place due to their long branching, but they likely belong to either Errantia or Sedentaria.
[src:annelid/aciculata] Errantia is, along with Sedentaria, one of the two old orders of the paraphyletic class "Polychaeta".
[src:annelid/aciculata] In 1977 the zoologist Kristian Fauchald split Errantia into three orders: Phyllodocida, Amphinomida and Eunicida, giving way to this classification.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:annelid/acidobacteriota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:annelid/acoela] The etymology of "acoel" is from the Ancient Greek words ἀ (*a*), the *alpha privative*, expressing negation or absence, and κοιλία (*koilía*), meaning "cavity".
[src:annelid/acoela] This refers to the fact that acoels have a structure lacking a fluid-filled body cavity.
[src:annelid/acoela] Acoels are very small, flattened worms, usually under 2 millimetres (0.079 in) in length, but some larger species, such as *Symsagittifera roscoffensis*, may reach up to 15 millimetres (0.59 in).
[src:annelid/acoela] They are bilaterally symmetric and microscopic.
[src:annelid/acoela] They are found worldwide in marine and brackish waters, usually having a benthic lifestyle, although some species are epibionts.
[src:annelid/acoela] Two species, *Limnoposthia polonica* and *Oligochoerus limnophilus*, are known to live in freshwater.
[src:annelid/acoela] Species in the family Convolutidae often form endosymbiotic relationship with microalgae.
[src:annelid/acoela] In one of the genera, *Waminoa*, the algae are transmitted vertically from parents to offspring.
[src:annelid/acoela] In addition to Convolutidae, there appears to be a potential new and yet unnamed family of acoels that also live in relationships with microalgal endosymbionts.
[src:annelid/acoela] Members of the class Acoela lack a conventional gut, so that the mouth opens directly into the mesenchyme, i.e., the layer of tissue that fills the body.
[src:annelid/acoela] Digestion is accomplished by means of a syncytium that forms a vacuole around ingested food.
[src:annelid/acoela] There are no epithelial cells lining the digestive vacuole, but in the families Diopisthoporidae, Hallangiidae, Hofsteniidae, and Solenofilomorphidae, and the genera Oligochoerus (Convolutidae) and Proporus (Proporidae), there is a short pharynx leading from the mouth to the vacuole.
[src:annelid/acoela] All other bilateral animals (apart from tapeworms) have a gut lined with epithelial cells.
[src:annelid/acoela] As a result, the acoels appear to be solid-bodied.
[src:annelid/acoela] The Acoela provide interesting insights into early animal evolution and development.
[src:annelid/acoela] The most thoroughly studied animal in this group is the species *Isodiametra pulchra*.
[src:annelid/acoela] Acoela used to be classified in the phylum Platyhelminthes.
[src:annelid/acoela] However, Acoela was separated from this phylum after molecular analyses showed that it had diverged before the three main bilaterian clades had formed, making flatworms, as traditionally understood, an evolutionary grade rather than a monophyletic clade.
[src:annelid/acoela] Acoela is considered a member of the phylum Xenacoelomorpha, within which it is sister to the Nemertodermatida.
[src:annelid/acoela] However, this apparent relationship may result erroneously from long branch attraction, with Acoela instead forming a clade with *Xenoturbella*.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] The term "acoelomorph" derives from the Ancient Greek words ἀ (*a*), the *alpha privative*, expressing negation or absence, κοιλία (*koilía*), meaning "cavity", and μορφή (*morphḗ*), meaning "form".
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] This refers to the fact that acoelomorphs have a structure lacking a fluid-filled body cavity.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] The subphylum Acoelomorpha is divided into two classes.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] There are at least 408 described species, with a majority of these falling within the Crucimusculata infraorder in Acoela.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] The soft bodies and the lack of some of the key bilaterian traits make acoelomorphs difficult to classify.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] Traditionally, based on phenotypic features, acoelomorphs were considered to belong to the phylum Platyhelminthes, which was long seen as the sister group to all other bilaterian phyla.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] However, a series of molecular phylogenetics studies at the hinge between the 20th and 21st centuries demonstrated that they are fast-evolving organisms not closely related to platyhelminthes, therefore involving the polyphyly of flatworms.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] Acoelomorpha appeared to constitute a separate, deep-branching phylum, the kingpin of bilaterian evolution.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] Yet their evolutionary affinities remain enigmatic, as they might be the sister-group either to all other bilateral animals or to all deuterostomes.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] Resolving this debate would indicate whether acoelomorphs are simple or simplified.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] If they are the sister group to Bilateria, it would point to a simple body plan for the first bilaterian.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] Alternatively, if acoelomorphs are related to deuterostomes, this would imply that their organisation is the result of secondary simplification.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] In addition, comparative analyses of morphological, developmental, and molecular characters raised two points.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] Acoelomorphs resemble flatworms in many respects, but have a simpler anatomy, not even having a gut.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] Like flatworms, they have no circulatory or respiratory systems, but they also lack an excretory system.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] They lack body cavities (acoelomate structure), a hindgut, or an anus.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] The epidermal cells of acoelomorphs are unable to proliferate, a feature that is only shared with rhabditophoran flatworms and was, for some time, considered strong evidence for the position of Acoelomorpha within Platyhelminthes.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] In both groups, the epidermis is renewed from mesodermal stem cells.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] The nervous system of acoelomorphs is formed by a set of longitudinal nerve bundles beneath the ciliated epidermis.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] Close to the anterior end, these bundles are united by a ring commissure, but do not form a true brain, although it is hypothesized that such organization was the precursor of the cephalization of the nerve system in more derived bilaterians.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] After decapitation, such a "brain" (rather, a *cerebroid ganglion*) regenerates in a few weeks.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] The sensory organs include a statocyst, which presumably helps them orient to gravity, and, in some cases, ancestral pigment-spot ocelli capable of detecting light.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] Acoelomorphs are simultaneous hermaphrodites but have no gonads and no ducts associated with the female reproductive system.
[src:annelid/acoelomorpha] Instead, gametes are produced from the mesenchymal cells that fill the body between the epidermis and the digestive vacuole.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The **acorn worms** or **Enteropneusta** are a hemichordate class of invertebrates.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The closest non-hemichordate relatives of the Enteropneusta are the echinoderms.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] There are 111 known species of acorn worm in the world, the main species for research being *Saccoglossus kowalevskii*.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Two families—Harrimaniidae and Ptychoderidae—separated at least 370 million years ago.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Until recently, it was thought that all species lived in the sediment on the seabed, subsisting as deposit feeders or suspension feeders.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] However, the early 21st century has seen the description of a new family, the Torquaratoridae, evidently limited to the deep sea, in which most of the species crawl on the surface of the ocean bottom and alternatively rise into the water column, evidently to drift to new foraging sites.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] It is assumed that the ancestors of acorn worms used to live in tubes like their relatives Pterobranchia, but that they eventually started to live a safer and more sheltered existence in sediment burrows instead.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The body length normally range from 2 centimetres (0.79 in) to 2.5 metres (8 ft 2 in) (*Balanoglossus gigas*), but one species, *Meioglossus psammophilus*, only reach 0.6 millimetres (0.024 in).
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Due to secretions containing elements like iodine, the animals have an iodoform-like smell.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Most acorn worms range from 9 to 45 centimetres (3.5 to 17.7 in) in length, with the largest species, *Balanoglossus gigas*, reaching 1.5 metres (5 ft) or more.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The body is made up of three main parts: an acorn-shaped proboscis, a short fleshy collar that lies behind it, and a long, worm-like trunk.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The creature's mouth is located at the collar behind the proboscis.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The skin is covered with cilia as well as glands that secrete mucus.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Some produce a bromide compound that gives them a medicinal smell and might protect them from bacteria and predators.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Acorn worms move only sluggishly, using ciliary action and peristalsis of the proboscis.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Many acorn worms are detritus feeders, eating sand or mud and extracting organic detritus.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Others feed on organic material suspended in the water, which they can draw into the mouth using the cilia on the gill bars.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Research indicates that the rate of feeding of acorn worms that are detritus feeders is dependent on food availability and flow rate.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] A groove lined with cilia lies just in front of the mouth and directs suspended food into the mouth and may allow the animal to taste.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The mouth cavity is tubular, with a narrow diverticulum or stomochord extending up into the proboscis.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] This diverticulum was once thought to be homologous with the notochord of chordates, hence the name "hemichordate" for the phylum.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The mouth opens posteriorly into a pharynx with a row of gill slits along either side.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The remainder of the digestive system consists of an oesophagus and intestine; there is no stomach.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] In some families there are openings in the dorsal surface of the oesophagus connecting to the external surface, through which water from the food can be squeezed, helping to concentrate it.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Digestion occurs in the intestine, with food material being pulled through by cilia, rather than by muscular action.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Acorn worms breathe by drawing in oxygenated water through their mouth.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The water then flows out the animal's gills which are on its trunk.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Thus, the acorn worm breathes about the same way as fish.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Acorn worms have an open circulatory system, in which the blood flows through the tissues sinuses.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] A dorsal blood vessel in the mesentery above the gut delivers blood to a sinus in the proboscis that contains a muscular sac acting as a heart.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Unlike the hearts of most other animals, however, this structure is a closed fluid-filled vesicle whose interior does not connect directly to the blood system.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Nonetheless, it does regularly pulsate, helping to push blood through the surrounding sinuses.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] From the central sinus in the collar, blood flows to a complex series of sinuses and peritoneal folds in the proboscis.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] This set of structures is referred to as a *glomerulus* and may have an excretory function, since acorn worms otherwise have no defined excretory system.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] From the proboscis, blood flows into a single blood vessel running underneath the digestive tract, from which smaller sinuses supply blood to the trunk, and back into the dorsal vessel.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The blood of acorn worms is colourless and acellular.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Acorn worms continually form new gill slits as they grow in size, with some older individuals of species like *Balanoglossus aurantiacus* having more than a hundred on each side.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The microscopic species *Meioglossus psammophilus* has just a single gill slit.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The gills in some acorn worms have cartilaginous support structures.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Each slit consists of a branchial chamber opening to the pharynx through a U-shaped cleft and to the exterior through a dorso-lateral pore (see diagram below).
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Cilia push water through the slits, maintaining a constant flow.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The tissues surrounding the slits are well supplied with blood sinuses.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] A plexus of nerves lies underneath the skin, and is concentrated into both dorsal and ventral nerve cords.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] While the ventral cord runs only as far as the collar, the dorsal cord reaches into the proboscis, and is partially separated from the epidermis in that region.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] This part of the dorsal nerve cord is often hollow, and may well be homologous with the brain of vertebrates.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] In acorn worms, it seems to be primarily involved with coordinating muscular action of the body during burrowing and crawling.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Acorn worms have no eyes, ears or other special sense organs, except for the ciliary organ in front of the mouth, which appears to be involved in filter feeding and perhaps taste.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] There are, however, numerous nerve endings throughout the skin.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Acorn worms have a Y-shaped nuchal skeleton that starts their proboscis and collar on their ventral side.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The length of the horns of the nuchal skeleton varies between species.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Acorn worms have a circulatory system with a heart that also functions as a kidney.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Acorn worms have gill-like structures that they use for breathing, similar to the gills of primitive fish.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Therefore, acorn worms are sometimes said to be a link between classical invertebrates and vertebrates.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Some also have a postanal tail which may be homologous to the post-anal tail of vertebrates.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] An interesting trait is that its three-section body plan is no longer present in the vertebrates, except for the anatomy of the frontal neural tube, later developed into a brain which is divided into three main parts.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] This means some of the original anatomy of the early chordate ancestors is still present even if it is not always visible.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] One theory is that the three-part body originates from an early common ancestor of all the deuterostomes, and maybe even from a common bilateral ancestor of both the deuterostomes and protostomes.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Studies have shown that the gene expression in the embryo share three of the same signaling centers that shape the brains of all vertebrates, but instead of taking part in the formation of their neural system, they are controlling the development of the different body regions.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The internal relationships within the Enteropneusta are shown below.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The tree is based on 16S +18S rRNA sequence data and phylogenomic studies from multiple sources, with the families Harrimaniidae and Ptychoderidae recovered as non-monophyletic.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Acorn worms are rarely seen by humans because of their lifestyle.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] They live in U-shaped burrows on the sea-bed, from the shoreline down to a depth of 10,000 ft.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The worms lie there with the proboscis sticking out of one opening in the burrow.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Acorn worms are generally slow burrowers.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] To obtain food, many acorn worms swallow sand or mud that contains organic matter and microorganisms in the manner of earthworms (this is known as deposit feeding).
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] At low tide, they stick out their rear ends at the surface and excrete coils of processed sediments (casts).
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Another method that some acorn worms use to obtain food is to collect suspended particles of organic matter and microbes from the water.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Acorn worms are dioecious, having separate biological sexes, although at least some species are also capable of asexual reproduction in the form of fragmentation.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] They have paired gonads, which lie close to the pharynx and release the gametes through a small pore near to the gill slits.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The female lays a large number of eggs embedded in a gelatinous mass of mucus, which are then externally fertilized by the male before water currents break up the mass and disperse the individual eggs.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] In most species, the eggs hatch into planktonic larvae with elongated bodies covered in cilia.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] In some species, these develop directly into adults, but in others, there is a free-swimming intermediate stage referred to as a *tornaria* larva.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] These are very similar in appearance to the bipinnaria larvae of starfishes, with convoluted bands of cilia running around the body.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] Since the embryonic development of the blastula within the egg is also very similar to that of echinoderms, this suggests a close phylogenetic link between the two groups.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] After a number of days or weeks, a groove begins to form around the larval midsection, with the anterior portion eventually destined to become the proboscis, while the remainder forms the collar and trunk.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] The larvae eventually settle down and change into tiny adults to take on the burrowing lifestyle.
[src:annelid/acorn-worm] A few species, such as *Saccoglossus kowalevskii*, lack even the planktonic larval stage, hatching directly as miniature adults.
[src:annelid/annelid] Annelids are bilaterally symmetrical, triploblastic, coelomate, invertebrate organisms.
[src:annelid/annelid] They also have parapodia for locomotion.
[src:annelid/annelid] Most textbooks still use the traditional division into Polychaetes (almost all marine), Oligochaetes (which include earthworms) and Hirudinea (leech-like species).
[src:annelid/annelid] Cladistic research since 1997 has radically changed this scheme, viewing leeches as a sub-group of oligochaetes and oligochaetes as a sub-group of polychaetes.
[src:annelid/annelid] In addition, the Pogonophora, Echiura and Sipuncula, previously regarded as separate phyla, are now regarded as sub-groups of polychaetes.
[src:annelid/annelid] Annelids are considered members of the Lophotrochozoa, a "super-phylum" of protostomes that also includes molluscs, brachiopods, and nemerteans.
[src:annelid/annelid] The basic annelid form consists of multiple segments called metameres.
[src:annelid/annelid] Each segment has the same sets of organs and, in most polychaetes, has a pair of parapodia that many species use for locomotion.
[src:annelid/annelid] Septa separate the segments of many species, but are poorly defined or absent in others, and Echiura and Sipuncula show no obvious signs of segmentation.
[src:annelid/annelid] In species with well-developed septa, the blood circulates entirely within blood vessels, and the vessels in segments near the front ends of these species are often built up with muscles that act as hearts.
[src:annelid/annelid] The septa of such species also enable them to change the shapes of individual segments, which facilitates movement by peristalsis ("ripples" that pass along the body) or by undulations that improve the effectiveness of the parapodia.
[src:annelid/annelid] In species with incomplete septa or none, the blood circulates through the main body cavity without any kind of pump, and there is a wide range of locomotory techniques – some burrowing species turn their pharynges inside out to drag themselves through the sediment.
[src:annelid/annelid] Earthworms are oligochaetes that support terrestrial food chains both as prey and predators, and in some regions are important in aeration and enriching of soil.
[src:annelid/annelid] The burrowing of marine polychaetes, which may constitute up to a third of all species in near-shore environments, encourages the development of ecosystems by enabling water and oxygen to penetrate the sea floor.
[src:annelid/annelid] In addition to improving soil fertility, annelids serve humans as food and as bait.
[src:annelid/annelid] Scientists observe annelids to monitor the quality of marine and fresh water.
[src:annelid/annelid] Although bloodletting is used far less frequently by doctors now than it once was, some leech species are regarded as endangered because they have been over-harvested for this purpose in the last few centuries.
[src:annelid/annelid] Ragworms' jaws are studied by engineers, as they offer an exceptional combination of lightness and strength.
[src:annelid/annelid] Since annelids are soft-bodied, their fossils are rare – mostly jaws and the mineralized tubes that some of the species secreted.
[src:annelid/annelid] Although some late Ediacaran fossils may represent annelids, the oldest known fossil that is identified with confidence comes from about 518 million years ago in the early Cambrian period.
[src:annelid/annelid] Fossils of most modern mobile polychaete groups appeared by the end of the Carboniferous period, about 299 million years ago.
[src:annelid/annelid] Palaeontologists disagree about whether some body fossils from the mid Ordovician, about 472 to 461 million years ago, are the remains of oligochaetes, and the earliest indisputable fossils of the group appear in the Paleogene period, which began 66 million years ago.
[src:annelid/annelid] Annelid translates to "little ringed ones;" literally, "little ring-shaped." *Annel* + *id* = "little ring" + "shape/form".
[src:annelid/annelid] Annelid comes from the French *annelés* "ringed ones", derived from the Latin *annulus* "little ring" (itself derived from *anus* "ring").
[src:annelid/annelid] There are over 22,000 living annelid species, ranging in size from microscopic to the Australian giant Gippsland earthworm and *Amynthas mekongianus*, which can both grow up to 3 meters (9.8 ft) long to the largest annelid, *Microchaetus rappi* which can grow up to 6.7 m (22 ft).
[src:annelid/annelid] Mitogenomic and phylogenomic analysis also implies that Orthonectida, a group of extremely simplified parasites traditionally placed in Mesozoa, are actually reduced annelids.
[src:annelid/annelid] Research suggest that also nemerteans are annelids, with Oweniidae and Magelonidae as their closest relatives.
[src:annelid/annelid] No single feature distinguishes annelids from other invertebrate phyla, but they have a distinctive combination of features.
[src:annelid/annelid] Their bodies are long, with segments that are divided externally by shallow ring-like constrictions called annuli and internally by septa ("partitions") at the same points, although in some species the septa are incomplete and in a few cases missing.
[src:annelid/annelid] Most of the segments contain the same sets of organs, although sharing a common gut, circulatory system and nervous system makes them inter-dependent.
[src:annelid/annelid] Under the naked skin, well-developed muscles can be found.
[src:annelid/annelid] They have a closed circuit vascular system with loose hemoglobine where the blood makes its entire circuit via blood vessels.
[src:annelid/annelid] In addition to Sipuncula and Echiura, also lineages like *Lobatocerebrum*, *Diurodrilus* and *Polygordius* have lost their segmentation, but these are the exceptions from the rule.
[src:annelid/annelid] Most of an annelid's body consists of segments that are practically identical, having the same sets of internal organs and external chaetae (Greek χαιτη, meaning "hair") and, in some species, appendages.
[src:annelid/annelid] The frontmost and rearmost sections are not regarded as true segments as they do not contain the standard sets of organs and do not develop in the same way as the true segments.
[src:annelid/annelid] The frontmost section, called the prostomium (Greek προ- meaning "in front of" and στομα meaning "mouth") contains the brain and sense organs, while the rearmost, called the pygidium (Greek πυγιδιον, meaning "little tail") or periproct contains the anus, generally on the underside.
[src:annelid/annelid] The first section behind the prostomium, called the peristomium (Greek περι- meaning "around" and στομα meaning "mouth"), is regarded by some zoologists as not a true segment, but in some polychaetes the peristomium has chetae and appendages like those of other segments.
[src:annelid/annelid] The segments develop one at a time from a growth zone just ahead of the pygidium, so that an annelid's youngest segment is just in front of the growth zone while the peristomium is the oldest.
[src:annelid/annelid] This pattern is called teloblastic growth.
[src:annelid/annelid] Some groups of annelids, including all leeches, have fixed maximum numbers of segments, while others add segments throughout their lives.
[src:annelid/annelid] The phylum's name is derived from the Latin word *annelus*, meaning "little ring".
[src:annelid/annelid] Annelids' cuticles are made of collagen fibers, usually in layers that spiral in alternating directions so that the fibers cross each other.
[src:annelid/annelid] These are secreted by the one-cell deep epidermis (outermost skin layer).
[src:annelid/annelid] A few marine annelids that live in tubes lack cuticles, but their tubes have a similar structure, and mucus-secreting glands in the epidermis protect their skins.
[src:annelid/annelid] Under the epidermis is the dermis, which is made of connective tissue, in other words a combination of cells and non-cellular materials such as collagen.
[src:annelid/annelid] Below this are two layers of muscles, which develop from the lining of the coelom (body cavity): circular muscles make a segment longer and slimmer when they contract, while under them are longitudinal muscles, usually four distinct strips, whose contractions make the segment shorter and fatter.
[src:annelid/annelid] But several families have lost the circular muscles, and it has been suggested that the lack of circular muscles is a plesiomorphic character in Annelida.
[src:annelid/annelid] Some annelids also have oblique internal muscles that connect the underside of the body to each side.
[src:annelid/annelid] The setae ("hairs") of annelids project out from the epidermis to provide traction and other capabilities.
[src:annelid/annelid] The simplest are unjointed and form paired bundles near the top and bottom of each side of each segment.
[src:annelid/annelid] The parapodia ("limbs") of annelids that have them often bear more complex chetae at their tips – for example jointed, comb-like or hooked.
[src:annelid/annelid] Chetae are made of moderately flexible β-chitin and are formed by follicles, each of which has a chetoblast ("hair-forming") cell at the bottom and muscles that can extend or retract the cheta.
[src:annelid/annelid] The chetoblasts produce chetae by forming microvilli, fine hair-like extensions that increase the area available for secreting the cheta.
[src:annelid/annelid] When the cheta is complete, the microvilli withdraw into the chetoblast, leaving parallel tunnels that run almost the full length of the cheta.
[src:annelid/annelid] Hence annelids' chetae are structurally different from the setae ("bristles") of arthropods, which are made of the more rigid α-chitin, have a single internal cavity, and are mounted on flexible joints in shallow pits in the cuticle.
[src:annelid/annelid] Nearly all polychaetes have parapodia that function as limbs, while other major annelid groups lack them.
[src:annelid/annelid] Parapodia are unjointed paired extensions of the body wall, and their muscles are derived from the circular muscles of the body.
[src:annelid/annelid] They are often supported internally by one or more large, thick chetae.
[src:annelid/annelid] The parapodia of burrowing and tube-dwelling polychaetes are often just ridges whose tips bear hooked chetae.
[src:annelid/annelid] In active crawlers and swimmers the parapodia are often divided into large upper and lower paddles on a very short trunk, and the paddles are generally fringed with chetae and sometimes with cirri (fused bundles of cilia) and gills.
[src:annelid/annelid] The brain generally forms a ring round the pharynx (throat), consisting of a pair of ganglia (local control centers) above and in front of the pharynx, linked by double ventral nerve cords either side of the pharynx to another pair of ganglia just below and behind it.
[src:annelid/annelid] The brains of polychaetes are generally in the prostomium, while those of clitellates are in the peristomium or sometimes the first segment behind the prostomium.
[src:annelid/annelid] In some very mobile and active polychaetes the brain is enlarged and more complex, with visible hindbrain, midbrain and forebrain sections.
[src:annelid/annelid] The rest of the central nervous system, the ventral nerve cord, is generally "ladder-like", consisting of a pair of nerve cords that run through the bottom part of the body and have in each segment paired ganglia linked by a transverse connection.
[src:annelid/annelid] From each segmental ganglion a branching system of local nerves runs into the body wall and then encircles the body.
[src:annelid/annelid] However, in most polychaetes the two main nerve cords are fused, and in the tube-dwelling genus *Owenia* the single nerve chord has no ganglia and is located in the epidermis.
[src:annelid/annelid] As in arthropods, each muscle fiber (cell) is controlled by more than one neuron, and the speed and power of the fiber's contractions depends on the combined effects of all its neurons.
[src:annelid/annelid] Vertebrates have a different system, in which one neuron controls a group of muscle fibers.
[src:annelid/annelid] Most annelids' longitudinal nerve trunks include giant axons (the output signal lines of nerve cells).
[src:annelid/annelid] Their large diameter decreases their resistance, which allows them to transmit signals exceptionally fast.
[src:annelid/annelid] This enables these worms to withdraw rapidly from danger by shortening their bodies.
[src:annelid/annelid] Experiments have shown that cutting the giant axons prevents this escape response but does not affect normal movement.
[src:annelid/annelid] The sensors are primarily single cells that detect light, chemicals, pressure waves and contact, and are present on the head, appendages (if any) and other parts of the body.
[src:annelid/annelid] Nuchal ("on the neck") organs are paired, ciliated structures found only in polychaetes, and are thought to be chemosensors.
[src:annelid/annelid] Some polychaetes also have various combinations of ocelli ("little eyes") that detect the direction from which light is coming and camera eyes or compound eyes that can probably form images.
[src:annelid/annelid] The compound eyes probably evolved independently of arthropods' eyes.
[src:annelid/annelid] Some tube-worms use ocelli widely spread over their bodies to detect the shadows of fish, so that they can quickly withdraw into their tubes.
[src:annelid/annelid] Some burrowing and tube-dwelling polychaetes have statocysts (tilt and balance sensors) that indicate which way is down.
[src:annelid/annelid] A few polychaete genera have on the undersides of their heads palps that are used both in feeding and as "feelers", and some of these also have antennae that are structurally similar but probably are used mainly as "feelers".
[src:annelid/annelid] Most annelids have a pair of coelomata (body cavities) in each segment, separated from other segments by septa and from each other by vertical mesenteries.
[src:annelid/annelid] Each septum forms a sandwich with connective tissue in the middle and mesothelium (membrane that serves as a lining) from the preceding and following segments on either side.
[src:annelid/annelid] Each mesentery is similar except that the mesothelium is the lining of each of the pair of coelomata, and the blood vessels and, in polychaetes, the main nerve cords are embedded in it.
[src:annelid/annelid] The mesothelium is made of modified epitheliomuscular cells; in other words, their bodies form part of the epithelium but their bases extend to form muscle fibers in the body wall.
[src:annelid/annelid] The mesothelium may also form radial and circular muscles on the septa, and circular muscles around the blood vessels and gut.
[src:annelid/annelid] Many annelids move by peristalsis (waves of contraction and expansion that sweep along the body), or flex the body while using parapodia to crawl or swim.
[src:annelid/annelid] In these animals the septa enable the circular and longitudinal muscles to change the shape of individual segments, by making each segment a separate fluid-filled "balloon".
[src:annelid/annelid] The fluid in the coelomata contains coelomocyte cells that defend the animals against parasites and infections.
[src:annelid/annelid] In some species coelomocytes may also contain a respiratory pigment – red hemoglobin in some species, green chlorocruorin in others (dissolved in the plasma) – and provide oxygen transport within their segments.
[src:annelid/annelid] Respiratory pigment is also dissolved in the blood plasma.
[src:annelid/annelid] Species with well-developed septa generally also have blood vessels running all long their bodies above and below the gut, the upper one carrying blood forwards while the lower one carries it backwards.
[src:annelid/annelid] Networks of capillaries in the body wall and around the gut transfer blood between the main blood vessels and to parts of the segment that need oxygen and nutrients.
[src:annelid/annelid] Both of the major vessels, especially the upper one, can pump blood by contracting.
[src:annelid/annelid] In some annelids the forward end of the upper blood vessel is enlarged with muscles to form a heart, while in the forward ends of many earthworms some of the vessels that connect the upper and lower main vessels function as hearts.
[src:annelid/annelid] Species with poorly developed or no septa generally have no blood vessels and rely on the circulation within the coelom for delivering nutrients and oxygen.
[src:annelid/annelid] However, leeches and their closest relatives have a body structure that is very uniform within the group but significantly different from that of other annelids, including other members of the Clitellata.
[src:annelid/annelid] In leeches there are no septa, the connective tissue layer of the body wall is so thick that it occupies much of the body, and the two coelomata are widely separated and run the length of the body.
[src:annelid/annelid] They function as the main blood vessels, although they are side-by-side rather than upper and lower.
[src:annelid/annelid] However, they are lined with mesothelium, like the coelomata and unlike the blood vessels of other annelids.
[src:annelid/annelid] Leeches generally use suckers at their front and rear ends to move like inchworms.
[src:annelid/annelid] The anus is on the upper surface of the pygidium.
[src:annelid/annelid] In some annelids, including earthworms, all respiration is via the skin.
[src:annelid/annelid] However, many polychaetes and some clitellates (the group to which earthworms belong) have gills associated with most segments, often as extensions of the parapodia in polychaetes.
[src:annelid/annelid] The gills of tube-dwellers and burrowers usually cluster around whichever end has the stronger water flow.
[src:annelid/annelid] Feeding structures in the mouth region vary widely, and have little correlation with the animals' diets.
[src:annelid/annelid] Many polychaetes have a muscular pharynx that can be everted (turned inside out to extend it).
[src:annelid/annelid] In these animals the foremost few segments often lack septa so that, when the muscles in these segments contract, the sharp increase in fluid pressure from all these segments everts the pharynx very quickly.
[src:annelid/annelid] Two families, the Eunicidae and Phyllodocidae, have evolved jaws, which can be used for seizing prey, biting off pieces of vegetation, or grasping dead and decaying matter.
[src:annelid/annelid] On the other hand, some predatory polychaetes have neither jaws nor eversible pharynges.
[src:annelid/annelid] Selective deposit feeders generally live in tubes on the sea-floor and use palps to find food particles in the sediment and then wipe them into their mouths.
[src:annelid/annelid] Filter feeders use "crowns" of palps covered in cilia that wash food particles towards their mouths.
[src:annelid/annelid] Non-selective deposit feeders ingest soil or marine sediments via mouths that are generally unspecialized.
[src:annelid/annelid] Some clitellates have sticky pads in the roofs of their mouths, and some of these can evert the pads to capture prey.
[src:annelid/annelid] Leeches often have an eversible proboscis, or a muscular pharynx with two or three teeth.
[src:annelid/annelid] The gut is generally an almost straight tube supported by the mesenteries (vertical partitions within segments), and ends with the anus on the underside of the pygidium.
[src:annelid/annelid] However, in members of the tube-dwelling family Siboglinidae the gut is blocked by a swollen lining that houses symbiotic bacteria, which can make up 15% of the worms' total weight.
[src:annelid/annelid] The bacteria convert inorganic matter – such as hydrogen sulfide and carbon dioxide from hydrothermal vents, or methane from seeps – to organic matter that feeds themselves and their hosts, while the worms extend their palps into the gas flows to absorb the gases needed by the bacteria.
[src:annelid/annelid] Annelids with blood vessels use metanephridia to remove soluble waste products, while those without use protonephridia.
[src:annelid/annelid] Both of these systems use a two-stage filtration process, in which fluid and waste products are first extracted and these are filtered again to re-absorb any re-usable materials while dumping toxic and spent materials as urine.
[src:annelid/annelid] In annelids the points at which fluid enters the protonephridia or metanephridia are on the forward side of a septum while the second-stage filter and the nephridiopore (exit opening in the body wall) are in the following segment.
[src:annelid/annelid] Polychaetes can reproduce asexually, by dividing into two or more pieces or by budding off a new individual while the parent remains a complete organism.
[src:annelid/annelid] Some oligochaetes, such as *Aulophorus furcatus*, seem to reproduce entirely asexually, while others reproduce asexually in summer and sexually in autumn.
[src:annelid/annelid] Asexual reproduction in oligochaetes is always by dividing into two or more pieces, rather than by budding.
[src:annelid/annelid] However, leeches have never been seen reproducing asexually.
[src:annelid/annelid] Most polychaetes and oligochaetes also use similar mechanisms to regenerate after suffering damage.
[src:annelid/annelid] Two polychaete genera, *Chaetopterus* and *Dodecaceria*, can regenerate from a single segment, and others can regenerate even if their heads are removed.
[src:annelid/annelid] Annelids are the most complex animals that can regenerate after such severe damage.
[src:annelid/annelid] On the other hand, leeches cannot regenerate.
[src:annelid/annelid] It is thought that annelids were originally animals with two separate sexes, which released ova and sperm into the water via their nephridia.
[src:annelid/annelid] The fertilized eggs develop into trochophore larvae, which live as plankton.
[src:annelid/annelid] However, the lifecycles of most living polychaetes, which are almost all marine animals, are unknown, and only about 25% of the 300+ species whose lifecycles are known follow this pattern.
[src:annelid/annelid] About 14% use a similar external fertilization but produce yolk-rich eggs, which reduce the time the larva needs to spend among the plankton, or eggs from which miniature adults emerge rather than larvae.
[src:annelid/annelid] The rest care for the fertilized eggs until they hatch – some by producing jelly-covered masses of eggs which they tend, some by attaching the eggs to their bodies and a few species by keeping the eggs within their bodies until they hatch.
[src:annelid/annelid] These species use a variety of methods for sperm transfer; for example, in some the females collect sperm released into the water, while in others the males have a penis that inject sperm into the female.
[src:annelid/annelid] There is no guarantee that this is a representative sample of polychaetes' reproductive patterns, and it simply reflects scientists' current knowledge.
[src:annelid/annelid] Some polychaetes breed only once in their lives, while others breed almost continuously or through several breeding seasons.
[src:annelid/annelid] While most polychaetes remain of one sex all their lives, a significant percentage of species are full hermaphrodites or change sex during their lives.
[src:annelid/annelid] Most polychaetes whose reproduction has been studied lack permanent gonads, and it is uncertain how they produce ova and sperm.
[src:annelid/annelid] In a few species the rear of the body splits off and becomes a separate individual that lives just long enough to swim to a suitable environment, usually near the surface, and spawn.
[src:annelid/annelid] Most mature clitellates (the group that includes earthworms and leeches) are full hermaphrodites, although in a few leech species younger adults function as males and become female at maturity.
[src:annelid/annelid] All have well-developed gonads, and all copulate.
[src:annelid/annelid] Earthworms store their partners' sperm in spermathecae ("sperm stores") and then the clitellum produces a cocoon that collects ova from the ovaries and then sperm from the spermathecae.
[src:annelid/annelid] Fertilization and development of earthworm eggs takes place in the cocoon.
[src:annelid/annelid] Leeches' eggs are fertilized in the ovaries, and then transferred to the cocoon.
[src:annelid/annelid] In all clitellates the cocoon also either produces yolk when the eggs are fertilized or nutrients while they are developing.
[src:annelid/annelid] All clitellates hatch as miniature adults rather than larvae.
[src:annelid/annelid] Charles Darwin's book *The Formation of Vegetable Mould Through the Action of Worms* (1881) presented the first scientific analysis of earthworms' contributions to soil fertility.
[src:annelid/annelid] Some burrow while others live entirely on the surface, generally in moist leaf litter.
[src:annelid/annelid] Earthworms are also important prey for birds ranging in size from robins to storks, and for mammals ranging from shrews to badgers, and in some cases conserving earthworms may be essential for conserving endangered birds.
[src:annelid/annelid] Terrestrial annelids can be invasive in some situations.
[src:annelid/annelid] In the glaciated areas of North America, for example, almost all native earthworms are thought to have been killed by the glaciers and the worms currently found in those areas are all introduced from other areas, primarily from Europe, and, more recently, from Asia.
[src:annelid/annelid] Northern hardwood forests are especially negatively impacted by invasive worms through the loss of leaf duff, soil fertility, changes in soil chemistry and the loss of ecological diversity.
[src:annelid/annelid] Especially of concern is *Amynthas agrestis* and at least one state (Wisconsin) has listed it as a prohibited species.
[src:annelid/annelid] Earthworms migrate only a limited distance annually on their own, and the spread of invasive worms is increased rapidly by anglers and from worms or their cocoons in the dirt on vehicle tires or footwear.
[src:annelid/annelid] Marine annelids may account for over one-third of bottom-dwelling animal species around coral reefs and in tidal zones.
[src:annelid/annelid] Burrowing species increase the penetration of water and oxygen into the sea-floor sediment, which encourages the growth of populations of aerobic bacteria and small animals alongside their burrows.
[src:annelid/annelid] Although blood-sucking leeches do little direct harm to their victims, some transmit flagellates that can be very dangerous to their hosts.
[src:annelid/annelid] Some small tube-dwelling oligochaetes transmit myxosporean parasites that cause whirling disease in fish.
[src:annelid/annelid] Earthworms make a significant contribution to soil fertility.
[src:annelid/annelid] The rear end of the Palolo worm, a marine polychaete that tunnels through coral, detaches in order to spawn at the surface, and the people of Samoa regard these spawning modules as a delicacy.
[src:annelid/annelid] Anglers sometimes find that worms are more effective bait than artificial flies, and worms can be kept for several days in a tin lined with damp moss.
[src:annelid/annelid] Ragworms are commercially important as bait and as food sources for aquaculture, and there have been proposals to farm them in order to reduce over-fishing of their natural populations.
[src:annelid/annelid] Some marine polychaetes' predation on molluscs causes serious losses to fishery and aquaculture operations.
[src:annelid/annelid] Scientists study aquatic annelids to monitor the oxygen content, salinity and pollution levels in fresh and marine water.
[src:annelid/annelid] Accounts of the use of leeches for the medically dubious practice of blood-letting have come from China around 30 AD, India around 200 AD, ancient Rome around 50 AD and later throughout Europe.
[src:annelid/annelid] In the 19th century medical demand for leeches was so high that some areas' stocks were exhausted and other regions imposed restrictions or bans on exports, and *Hirudo medicinalis* is treated as an endangered species by both IUCN and CITES.
[src:annelid/annelid] More recently leeches have been used to assist in microsurgery, and their saliva has provided anti-inflammatory compounds and several important anticoagulants, one of which also prevents tumors from spreading..
[src:annelid/annelid] One particularly important microsurgical application is when fingers, toes, or ears are cut off, in which arteries can easily be mended but not veins; the leeches can help control this congestion until the veins can grow back into the appendage to be healed.
[src:annelid/annelid] Ragworms' jaws are strong but much lighter than the hard parts of many other organisms, which are biomineralized with calcium salts.
[src:annelid/annelid] These advantages have attracted the attention of engineers.
[src:annelid/annelid] Investigations showed that ragworm jaws are made of unusual proteins that bind strongly to zinc.
[src:annelid/annelid] Since annelids are soft-bodied, their fossils are rare.
[src:annelid/annelid] Polychaetes' fossil record consists mainly of the jaws that some species had and the mineralized tubes that some secreted.
[src:annelid/annelid] Some Ediacaran fossils such as *Dickinsonia* in some ways resemble polychaetes, but the similarities are too vague for these fossils to be classified with confidence.
[src:annelid/annelid] The small shelly fossil *Cloudina*, from 549 to 542 million years ago, has been classified by some authors as an annelid, but by others as a cnidarian (i.e. in the phylum to which jellyfish and sea anemones belong).
[src:annelid/annelid] Until 2008 the earliest fossils widely accepted as annelids were the polychaetes *Canadia* and *Burgessochaeta*, both from Canada's Burgess Shale, formed about 505 million years ago in the Middle Cambrian.
[src:annelid/annelid] *Myoscolex*, found in Australia and a little older than the Burgess Shale, was possibly an annelid.
[src:annelid/annelid] However, it lacks some typical annelid features and has features which are not usually found in annelids and some of which are associated with other phyla.
[src:annelid/annelid] Then Simon Conway Morris and John Peel reported *Phragmochaeta* from Sirius Passet, about 518 million years old, and concluded that it was the oldest annelid known to date.
[src:annelid/annelid] There has been vigorous debate about whether the Burgess Shale fossil *Wiwaxia* was a mollusc or an annelid.
[src:annelid/annelid] Polychaetes diversified in the early Ordovician, about 488 to 474 million years ago.
[src:annelid/annelid] It is not until the early Ordovician that the first annelid jaws are found, thus the crown-group cannot have appeared before this date and probably appeared somewhat later.
[src:annelid/annelid] By the end of the Carboniferous, about 299 million years ago, fossils of most of the modern mobile polychaete groups had appeared.
[src:annelid/annelid] Many fossil tubes look like those made by modern sessile polychaetes, but the first tubes clearly produced by polychaetes date from the Jurassic, less than 199 million years ago.
[src:annelid/annelid] In 2012, a 508 million year old species of annelid found near the Burgess Shale beds in British Columbia, *Kootenayscolex*, was found that changed the hypotheses about how the annelid head developed.
[src:annelid/annelid] It appears to have bristles on its head segment akin to those along its body, as if the head simply developed as a specialized version of a previously generic segment.
[src:annelid/annelid] An even earlier fossil, *Wenghuiia*, was discovered in 2010 from the Ediacaran Doushantuo Formation around 555 Ma, and as this genus resembles relatively derived annelids this suggests their origins are even further back.
[src:annelid/annelid] The earliest good evidence for oligochaetes occurs in the Tertiary period, which began 65 million years ago, and it has been suggested that these animals evolved around the same time as flowering plants in the early Cretaceous, from 130 to 90 million years ago.
[src:annelid/annelid] A trace fossil consisting of a convoluted burrow partly filled with small fecal pellets may be evidence that earthworms were present in the early Triassic period from 251 to 245 million years ago.
[src:annelid/annelid] Body fossils going back to the mid Ordovician, from 472 to 461 million years ago, have been tentatively classified as oligochaetes, but these identifications are uncertain and some have been disputed.
[src:annelid/annelid] Traditionally the annelids have been divided into two major groups, the polychaetes and clitellates.
[src:annelid/annelid] In turn the clitellates were divided into oligochaetes, which include earthworms, and hirudinomorphs, whose best-known members are leeches.
[src:annelid/annelid] For many years there was no clear arrangement of the approximately 80 polychaete families into higher-level groups.
[src:annelid/annelid] Subsequent molecular phylogenetics analyses on a similar scale presented similar conclusions.
[src:annelid/annelid] In 2007 Torsten Struck and colleagues compared three genes in 81 taxa, of which nine were outgroups, in other words not considered closely related to annelids but included to give an indication of where the organisms under study are placed on the larger tree of life.
[src:annelid/annelid] For a cross-check the study used an analysis of 11 genes (including the original 3) in ten taxa.
[src:annelid/annelid] This analysis agreed that clitellates, pogonophorans and echiurans were on various branches of the polychaete family tree.
[src:annelid/annelid] It also concluded that the classification of polychaetes into Scolecida, Canalipalpata and Aciculata was useless, as the members of these alleged groups were scattered all over the family tree derived from comparing the 81 taxa.
[src:annelid/annelid] It also placed sipunculans, generally regarded at the time as a separate phylum, on another branch of the polychaete tree, and concluded that leeches were a sub-group of oligochaetes rather than their sister-group among the clitellates.
[src:annelid/annelid] Rouse accepted the analyses based on molecular phylogenetics, and their main conclusions are now the scientific consensus, although the details of the annelid family tree remain uncertain.
[src:annelid/annelid] In addition to re-writing the classification of annelids and three previously independent phyla, the molecular phylogenetics analyses undermine the emphasis that decades of previous writings placed on the importance of segmentation in the classification of invertebrates.
[src:annelid/annelid] Polychaetes, which these analyses found to be the parent group, have completely segmented bodies, while polychaetes' echiurans and sipunculan offshoots are not segmented and pogonophores are segmented only in the rear parts of their bodies.
[src:annelid/annelid] It now seems that segmentation can appear and disappear much more easily in the course of evolution than was previously thought.
[src:annelid/annelid] The 2007 study also noted that the ladder-like nervous system, which is associated with segmentation, is less universal than previously thought in both annelids and arthropods.
[src:annelid/annelid] The updated phylogenetic tree of the annelid phylum is comprised by a grade of basal groups of polychaetes: Palaeoannelida, Chaetopteriformia and the Amphinomida/Sipuncula/*Lobatocerebrum* clade.
[src:annelid/annelid] This grade is followed by Pleistoannelida, the clade containing nearly all of annelid diversity, divided into two highly diverse groups: Sedentaria and Errantia.
[src:annelid/annelid] Sedentaria contains the clitellates, pogonophorans, echiurans and some archiannelids, as well as several polychaete groups.
[src:annelid/annelid] Errantia contains the eunicid and phyllodocid polychaetes, and several archiannelids.
[src:annelid/annelid] Some small groups, such as the Myzostomida, are more difficult to place due to long branching, but belong to either one of these large groups.
[src:annelid/annelid] Annelids are members of the protostomes, one of the two major superphyla of bilaterian animals – the other is the deuterostomes, which includes vertebrates.
[src:annelid/annelid] Within the protostomes, annelids used to be grouped with arthropods under the super-group Articulata ("jointed animals"), as segmentation is obvious in most members of both phyla.
[src:annelid/annelid] However, the genes that drive segmentation in arthropods do not appear to do the same in annelids.
[src:annelid/annelid] Arthropods and annelids both have close relatives that are unsegmented.
[src:annelid/annelid] It is at least as easy to assume that they evolved segmented bodies independently as it is to assume that the ancestral protostome or bilaterian was segmented and that segmentation disappeared in many descendant phyla.
[src:annelid/annelid] The current view is that annelids are grouped with molluscs, brachiopods and several other phyla that have lophophores (fan-like feeding structures) and/or trochophore larvae as members of Lophotrochozoa.
[src:annelid/annelid] Meanwhile, arthropods are now regarded as members of the Ecdysozoa ("animals that molt"), along with some phyla that are unsegmented.
[src:annelid/annelid] The "Lophotrochozoa" hypothesis is also supported by the fact that many phyla within this group, including annelids, molluscs, nemerteans and flatworms, follow a similar pattern in the fertilized egg's development.
[src:annelid/annelid] When their cells divide after the 4-cell stage, descendants of these four cells form a spiral pattern.
[src:annelid/annelid] In these phyla the "fates" of the embryo's cells, in other words the roles their descendants will play in the adult animal, are the same and can be predicted from a very early stage.
[src:annelid/annelid] Hence this development pattern is often described as "spiral determinate cleavage".
[src:annelid/annelid] Fossil discoveries lead to the hypothesis that Annelida and the lophophorates are more closely related to each other than any other phyla.
[src:annelid/annelid] Because of the body plan of lophotrochozoan fossils, a phylogenetic analysis found the lophophorates as the sister group of annelids.
[src:annelid/annelid] Both groups share in common: the presence of chaetae secreted by microvilli; paired, metameric coelomic compartments; and a similar metanephridial structure.
